tags.description: listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1992.   The original bank vault remains intact.  It is the only building in Grandfield which represents the Italian Renaissance Revival style of architecture.  The bank was chartered in Kell, Oklahoma
tags.name: Tillman County Bank

tags.description: Drs. W. A. Fuqua, Horace Wright and H. C. Harris built the 3-story hospital in 1920. The fourteen bed hospital had an operating room on the third floor as well as living quarters for the Fuqua family.
tags.name: Grandfield Hospital Building

tags.description: In the early years the City Grocery & Market was here.  Also occupying it was Medlock, Fuller and Aven Grocery stores.  In later years, Frank Tisdale had a Hotpoint appliance dealership and an electrical service here.
tags.name: Tisdale Electric Building

tags.description: In 1910 E. R. Sessions built this building for “E R Sessions Furniture & Undertaking.” Later, Sam Hasenmyer had “Sam’s Bargain House” here. Milton Tomlinson bought the property and it became the second T. G. & Y Store in the state.
tags.name: Tomlinson's Dime Store Building

tags.description: Blue Front Grocery owned by Earl Hines occupied this lot in the early years. In May 1915, the first Rexall Drug was opened by Dr. M F. Patterson and Harry Cratty, a pharmacist. In 1940, Thomas Vines operated Vines Grocery here.
tags.name: Vines Grocery Bldg.

tags.description: The Rexall Store and a beauty shop were in this building at one time before it moved to its final place next door. Hick & Hasenmyer Dept. Store moved to this location in 1957.
tags.name: Rexall

tags.description: Home State Bank was in this location in the early years for a time.  Midway Café, owned by A. C. Potts was here in 1913. In 1933, Ray Seay bought the property as “Seay’s Rexall Drug.”
tags.name: Midway Cafe/ Rexall Drug

tags.description: In the 1920’s Grandfield Bakery & Restaurant was here. Various other business operated here including T V Cafe during the 50’s.
tags.name: Old Pool Hall

tags.description: Miss Calla Cato began her millinery business in 1914 on East 2nd possibly moving to this location in the late 20’s or early 30’s. She retired in 1978 and sold the business to Bob Wyatt who ran the store as the “Lee Dawn Shop” until 1982.
tags.name: Cato's Style Shop

tags.description: C. L, Mount, who had been in business since 1908, built this building for a dry goods store in the teens. Ed Murray was manager and had an interest in the business. Murray bought Mounts share in the 30’s. In 1948 it became Gourley Dry Goods Store when.
tags.name: Grandfield Library

tags.description: Originally a 2-story building when Tant Grocery Supply & Land build it in 1908.    Stanley Mohr had his undertaking office in a part of the building in 1920 for a time.  In 1922, a fire broke out in the Grandfield Hardware Co. warehouse.
tags.name: MID-CONTINENT SUPPLY BUILDING

tags.description: Grandfield Hardware Co., J. J. Allen, Prop., F. L. Willingham Sheet Metal & Hardware, Standley Confectionery Store, R & N Café, Jones Barber Shop, Eva’s Café, Cowboy Plumbing, Roddy’s White Auto Store, Harvest Theater.
tags.name: HARVEST PLAYHOUSE BUILDINGS

tags.description: The Citizens Bank, Farmers & Merchants Bank. Dr. W. B Price, dentist, W. H. Purcell Real Estate and Ins. Agency. Herb Byrns Agency, Jake Hagy Ins. Agency
tags.name: Price Insurance

tags.description: J. L.Standley Bldg. in the 20’s, and Staley & Covington Dry Goods, R. L. Winchell Ins., a grocery store, a barber shop, a café, a tanning salon, and a beauty shop.  The Economy Store, Lone Star Gas and City Realty, and D & K Tax Service.
tags.name: WINCHELL INSURANCE BLDG.

tags.description: Now under restoration and owned by Mr.James Jackson Jr. it was first owned by Audry Teeter-Teeter Drug Store, "Pete" Humphreys Drug, radio and TV repair shop.
tags.name: HUMPHREYS DRUG STORE

tags.description: Cato Millinery was in a part of this place in 1917.  Norman Dry Goods Store in the 1920’s.  Louis “Cash” Wheeler Café n the 30’s.  Joe Pidsley's Grocery
tags.name: Joe's Grocery

tags.description: O. L. Phipps and C. W. Snyder in 1920 as Phipps-Snyder Co.  Dr. S. J. Draper, a dentist from Lawton.  In 1934, Fred, Frank and Grady Hood Ford dealership as Hood Motor Company. Grandfield Motor Company died in the Depression. O. E. Britton the Jack Varner
tags.name: Grandfield Motor Company (Ford)

tags.description: The Rock Island Depot Building is located at 201 South Bridge and was built in 1920.  The builder was the Chicago Rock Island and Pacific Railway.
tags.name: Rock Island Depot

tags.description: Built in 1919, placed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1992.  It is a two-story home of the Craftsman style of architecture and the Bungalow/Prairie Style.  It was built by William and Mabel (Donahoo) Hubbard.
tags.name: The Hubbard Mansion

tags.description: Listed in "Ripley's Believe It or Not" and built entirely from Tin Oil Cans!
tags.name: Tin Can Garage

tags.description: One of the First Grandfield Buildings listed by the National Registry of Historical Places
tags.name: Old Jailhouse

tags.description: Burial site of Great Kiowa Chief Yellow Bear, earlier  used by Buffalo Soldiers to send signals to Ft. Sill.
tags.name: Curtis Mound and Signal Hill

properties.name: Grandfield Post Office-United States Postal Service

tags.name: Grandfield Post Office-United States Postal Service
